body:
Rust-gdb give different information about generator in the code after I compile with opt-level=1 instead of opt-level=0.


This is the code:

```
#![feature(generators, generator_trait)]
use std::ops::Generator;
use std::pin::Pin;
use std::sync::atomic::{AtomicUsize, Ordering};
static A: AtomicUsize = AtomicUsize::new(0);
struct B;
fn temp(){
    println!(" ");
}
impl Drop for B {
    fn drop(&mut self) {
        A.fetch_add(1, Ordering::SeqCst);
    }
}
fn main() {
    let b = B;
    let mut foo = || {
        yield b;
    };
    drop(Pin::new(&mut foo).resume());
    temp();
}
```


I always set the break point at the "temp();" line at the end of the main function and print for "foo". 

When I use opt-level=0, the value shows "foo = generator = {B, 3}".
When I use opt-level=1, the value shows "foo = generator = {B, 0}".

I am not sure what the two values in the generator are, however I assume the optimization level should not change any value. It seems like a bug to me.

